Processing proteomics data using TMT-NEAT

  1. Use the TMT-NEAT RShiny application to process the proteomics data output from MaxQuant. Download the TMT-NEAT repository from Github. Unzip the folder and save it to an accessible location on your computer. Additionally, unzip the TEST.zip folder within the TMT-NEAT repository folder to obtain the data files.

  2. Open RStudio and use setwd() to change the working directory to the folder containing the TMT-NEAT scripts.

  3. Start the app by running the RUN_TMT.R script, either by entering source(RUN_TMT.R) into the R Console or by clicking the Run App button in the top right corner with the green arrow. A new window will open containing the TMT-NEAT app interface.

  4. First, process the protein abundance data (proteinGroups.csv) from the TEST folder using the parameters shown in Figure 1a. A number of output files will be produced including various quality control plots and tables. Save these files to a new folder.

  5. Repeat step 5 using the phosphosite data (Phospho (STY)sites.csv) from the TEST folder with the parameters shown in Figure 2b.

Figure 2. TMT-NEAT processing of protein abundance (a) and phosphosite (b) data. Important parameter differences between the two data types are highlighted with blue boxes.

Tips and Tricks

  1. Currently, TMT-NEAT only supports MaxQuant output tables which have been converted to comma-separated value (.csv) format using R, Microsoft Excel, or another text-editing software. TMT-NEAT may support more file types and/or output from other proteomics processing softwares in the future.

  2. This tutorial does not perform differential expression. Differential expression can be performed by selecting Yes under Differential Expression and defining the desired p- or q-value cutoff.

  3. Output files will be overwritten every time TMT-NEAT is run, so make sure to rename the output files after each run.
